        "Id": 49,
        "ContentTypeId": "0x0110002675B935B1E1CA40903215A1EC22F4C4",
        "Title": "Another LAF victory",
        "Body": "<div class=\"ExternalClassFB91A64DFC9847F8A9699EA5B246D584\"><p><span>In this case, “it” is the important three-day right to cancel under the Truth in Lending Act (TILA).<span>&#160; </span>Under a bad decision properly reversed by the Illinois Supreme Court, the appeals court had denied TILA’s right to cancel to a mortgagor who did not sign the underlying note.<span>&#160; </span>According to this flawed decision, a homeowner would not have the chance to reconsider and change her mind about mortgaging her home for a loan made to someone else.</span></p><div><span>&#160;</span></div><p></p><div><span>@Michelle Weinberg's client was a senior whose profiteering daughter tricked her into signing a mortgage so that she could get a loan and steal the equity from the home.<span>&#160; </span>Even though client risked losing her home, the trial court (in deference to the bad appellate decision noted above), held that she had no right to cancel the transaction because she did not sign the note.<span>&#160; </span></span></div><p></p><div><span>&#160;</span></div><p></p><div><span>Seeing that the Illinois Supreme Court had granted review of the bad appeals court decision, Michelle coordinated an amicus effort on behalf of LAF and national consumer groups.<span>&#160; </span>Fortunately, the Illinois Supreme Court paid heed to the consumer briefs and read the controlling TILA regulations which give the right to cancel to <i>any</i> consumer who signs a mortgage.<span>&#160; </span>In essence, the Court said that “any” means “any.”<span>&#160; </span>Michelle can now go back to the trial court and use the Supreme Court’s decision to her client’s advantage.<span>&#160; </span>Additional credits go to @James Brady, who worked on the amicus brief, and Elise Tincher, who worked on our client’s case.</span></div><p></p><div><span>&#160;</span></div><p></p><div><span>You can read the September 24 decision in Financial Freedom v. Standard Bank at&#58;</span></div><p></p><div><span>&#160;</span></div><p></p><div><span><a href=\"http&#58;//www.illinoiscourts.gov/Opinions/SupremeCourt/2015/117950.pdf\"><font color=\"#0000ff\"><u>http&#58;//www.illinoiscourts.gov/Opinions/SupremeCourt/2015/117950.pdf</u></font></a></span><br></div></div>",
