        "Id": 52,
        "ContentTypeId": "0x0110002675B935B1E1CA40903215A1EC22F4C4",
        "Title": "Juvenile Court Victory: Just Because You are Unavailable Doesn't Mean You Get to Be a Witness",
        "Body": "<div class=\"ExternalClassB83692A18BE54377BD03B03DA03DBB17\"><p>An outright win in Juvenile Court DCFS cases is unusual.&#160; So congratulate Steve and Colleen on this One. <br></p><p>This case involved an allegation that somehow our client&#160; (a young mom from Milwaukee visiting Chicago relatives) left her 2 children with a babysitter who then let them alone in a park and then someone brought them to a relative's house near the park.&#160; No one was hurt, but once DCFS was called .&#160; The court rejected our objections under the UCCJEA to jurisdiction, opened a case, and monitored the family in Wisconsin.&#160; Meanwhile the state was trying to see if it could actually prove that the client had done something wrong.&#160; The key was a witness whom the DCFS investigator appeared to misunderstand.&#160;&#160; The investigator claimed the witness said the client left the kids with a 9 year old; the witness told other investigators he never said any such thing.</p><p>The day before the trial the state gave notice that it was going to try to have the investigator testify to the hearsay statement of the witness under the 804 Unavailable Witness Exception.&#160; One big problem.&#160; While the state might have been able to show the witness was unavailable, the witness's testimony was not the type of testimony admitted under the 804(b) exceptions.&#160; Problem. It is so obvious that you need both unavailability and an 804(b) exception that almost no case says it outright. Research follows, Includes call to one of the reporters on the Illinois rules of evidence who says we are right but cannot think of case.&#160; Steve and Colleen objected using the research we have. Judge keeps testimony out. State fails to meet burden.&#160; No finding against parent.&#160; Case dismissed.&#160; Congrats to Steve, Colleen and our client.&#160; &#160; If you are interested in the 804(b) issue look at People v. Wright, 2015 IL App (1st) 123496,&#160; reh'g denied (June 24, 2015)<br> </p><p><br></p></div>",
