        "ContentTypeId": "0x0110002675B935B1E1CA40903215A1EC22F4C4",
        "Title": "Attempted Murder Victim Not Homeless",
        "Body": "<div class=\"ExternalClass0C606ADF74F044059E0F3C9B4C200841\"><p>When Mary Jackson refused to let her daughter's ex-boyfriend enter her apartment, he retaliated by setting her public housing unit on fire.&#160; After months of hospitalization, and after the housing authority refused to rent her a new apartment, Mary faced homelessness. The housing authority found Mary responsible for the fire because she let her daughter into her home when fleeing the abuser, and told Mary to go into assisted living.&#160; LAF's Neha Lall filed suit in federal court for violations of the Fair Housing Act, the Illinois Human Rights Act, and VAWA.&#160; Neha then convinced the housing authority to provide Mary with a new apartment and she is safely housed again.&#160; Her claim for money damages is still pending.&#160;</p><p>This story highlights LAF's work on behalf of D.V. survivors.&#160; Congratulations to Neha for her extraordinary efforts in helping this victim of abuse. <br></p></div>",
