        "Title": "Charity Care Argument Saves Nursing Home Resident from Eviction!",
        "Body": "<div class=\"ExternalClass1C31C0F5C0C9429094957A6D81B47DB1\"><p><span>Tony T. has been living at the same nursing home since early 2013.</span><span>&#160;</span><span>Back in 2013, for seven months while his Medicaid application was pending, the facility did not bill him for the money he owed.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>Once his Medicaid application was approved,they came to him with a bill for the approximately $14,000 he was supposed to have been paying the facility while the application was pending.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>Tony paid the facility consistently after that for two years.</span><span>&#160;</span><span>In 2015, the facility changed ownership and the new owners (a non-profit!) decided to issue Tony a notice of involuntary discharge for failing to pay the balance of the money he owed from 2013. </span><span>&#160;</span><span>Ombudsman Ash Lottes worked closely with Tony, investigating the involuntary discharge and gathering evidence regarding Tony’s bills.&#160;</span></p><p><span>Although he appealed the involuntary discharge, we were worried because Tony did owe the money and had no defense in the Department of Public Health eviction hearing.</span><span>&#160;</span><span>Until Alan Alop’s favorite argument against non-profit healthcare providers came to the rescue.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>After a letter from LAF asserting that the facility had an obligation to provide charity care, that Tony had a consumer fraud claim and that Tony was judgment proof, the facility capitulated.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>Within days, the facility offered to withdraw the involuntary discharge and forgive Tony’s debt to the facility.</span><span>&#160;</span><span>Shelmun Dashan and Suzanne Courtheoux identified the charity care argument and negotiated with the facilities attorneys. Ash Lottes was instrumental in identifying key issues and working with Tony to make sure the deal was in his interest.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>Tony gets to remain in his nursing home debt-free, without going through an involuntary discharge hearing! An unusual legal argument leads to a great result!</span></p></div>",
