        "Title": "Celebrating Volunteers - Peter Monahan",
        "Body": "<div class=\"ExternalClass22A52A16D7C24D28B321BD0206A815F3\"><p><span>Peter Monahan has been volunteering at LAF since 2013.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>Peter brings a wealth of knowledge and experience to his work at LAF.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>From 1983 to 1989, he was a partner at Hinshaw and Culbertson.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>After this he formed his own firm, Aholm, Monahan, Kaluke, Hay &amp; Oldenburg.</span><span>&#160;&#160;</span><span>In 2006, after 17 years at the firm, Peter decided to take a step back from the firm and get into consulting work.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>From 2006 to 2012, Peter worked for the Shakman Compliance.</span><br></p><p><span></span></p><p><span>After six years as a consultant, Peter wanted to get back into direct representation.<span>&#160; </span>He missed the face-to-face interaction with clients, and wanted to help people again.<span>&#160; </span>He saw LAF as an opportunity to do this without committing to a full time gig.<span>&#160;</span>So in late 2012, Peter sat down with Mara Block, Rich Cozzola, and JoAnn Villasenor and began volunteering in the Children and Families Practice Group.<span>&#160; </span>Working two or three days a week, Peter relishes in the opportunity to have his own case load and work directly with clients.<span>&#160; </span></span></p><p><span></span></p><p><span>When I asked Peter about one of his favorite victories at LAF,<span>&#160;he</span>&#160;told me about a child support battle.<span>&#160; </span>A mother had come to LAF looking to receive child support for her two children and the father had claimed that he was unemployed and unable to support them.<span>&#160; </span>When he showed up in court, the father had a cast on his leg, which the client thought was fake.<span>&#160; </span>Peter asked him to produce medical records for the injury, which he was unable to do. &#160;This convinced the judge to motion for a trial.</span></p><p><span></span></p><p><span>In discovery, Peter was having difficulty finding evidence that proved the father was employed, but he noticed that the client had an expensive looking haircut.<span>&#160; D</span>uring the trial, Peter asked how much the father spent on his haircuts.<span>&#160; </span>The man claimed to pay $25 every two weeks.<span>&#160; </span>The judge found it ridiculous that father could pay that much for a haircut, but couldn’t afford to provide for his two children, so he ordered the man to pay $100 per month in child support.</span></p><p><span>Still, finding this amount too low, Peter began looking for evidence to prove that the father was lying about being unemployed.<span>&#160; &#160;</span></span><span>As a last resort, He googled the father’s name and discovered a website that advertised multiple businesses owned by him.</span><span>&#160;</span><span>The website not only named the businesses, but advertised how much money he was making too.</span><span>&#160; </span><span>After this discovery, the judge ordered the father to pay $5000 in back pay to the client and upped the monthly support.</span></p><p><span></span></p><p><span>It’s this level of dedication that Peter brings to LAF day in and day out. &#160;</span></p><p><span>Thanks for all the work you do and keep catching those sleezeballs!</span></p></div>",
